<HEADLINE>
<P>
CSUN LEFT IN LURCH FOR FINALE IN SOCCER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By THERESA MUNOZ, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Just when the Cal State Northridge soccer team was hitting its stride, its 
season ended -- unexpectedly. 
</P>
<P>
The Matadors (9-7-3), winners of six of their past eight matches, were deprived 
of a season finale Friday at California. 
</P>
<P>
The Pacific 10 Conference school never had Northridge, a Division I 
independent, on its schedule. 
</P>
<P>
CSUN Coach Marwan Ass'ad said he scheduled the match last spring with Cal Coach 
Bill Coupe, who was replaced this fall by Dave Chaplick. Ass'ad was aware of 
the coaching change but failed to ensure that the match was still scheduled. 
</P>
<P>
"I should have done that," Ass'ad conceded. 
</P>
<P>
According to Northridge Athletic Director Bob Hiegert, Cal officials could have 
apprised CSUN of the situation at the beginning of the season when they 
received the schedule from CSUN. 
</P>
<P>
"At this point I'm not sure it is 100% Berkeley's fault," Hiegert said. "It 
might be 75% theirs and 25% ours. 
</P>
<P>
"We were fortunate we had played the minimal number of Division I games and 
that there were no playoff ramifications." 
</P>
<P>
The match was not bound by a contract, but that is not unusual. 
</P>
<P>
"I'd say 80% of our games we don't have contracts," Ass'ad said. "But from now 
on, of course, we will have a contract." 
</P>
<P>
If not for Tom Manning, Northridge assistant sports information director, CSUN 
would have flown to the Bay Area on Friday. Manning prevented what would have 
been a needless journey when he discovered the scheduling discrepancy Monday in 
a routine telephone call to Cal. 
</P>
<P>
"That would have been a disaster," Ass'ad said. "That would have really been 
embarrassing." 
</P>
<P>
According to Ass'ad, Chaplick told him Monday that he had a match with another 
team scheduled for Friday and knew nothing of a match with CSUN. 
</P>
<P>
But Kevin Reneau, Cal's assistant athletic director for media relations, said 
Cal has no match set for Friday. 
</P>
<P>
Chaplick was unavailable for comment. 
</P>
<P>
CSUN players learned of the situation hours before their 2-1 win Monday at Cal 
State Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
"It wasn't that bad," Matador junior midfielder Steve Linhart said. "We 
realized there's not a whole lot at stake, except the pride of winning. We knew 
there were no playoffs for us. 
</P>
<P>
"Since the season didn't go as we hoped we were ready to put it behind us and 
get ready for next year." 
</P>
<P>
The entire team is expected to return, including Danny Daniels, who scored a 
team-high 25 points (10 goals, five assists), Gus Cardenas and Bobby Reyes, who 
each scored 19 points. 
</P>
<P>
According to Ass'ad, Chaplick offered to schedule CSUN next season. 
</P>
</TEXT>
