<DOCID> 301233 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
November 1, 1990, Thursday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
San Gabriel Valley; Part J; Page 2; Column 1 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
145 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAN GABRIEL VALLEY DIGEST: PASADENA; 
</P>
<P>
JUDGE RULES FOR SWAP MEET 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
City officials must allow businessman Paul Cho to open a proposed swap 
meet-style store in Northwest Pasadena, a Los Angeles Superior Court judge has 
ruled. 
</P>
<P>
In his decision Tuesday on a lawsuit brought against the city by Cho, Judge 
David Yaffee ordered the city to inspect Cho's store at 625 N. Fair Oaks Ave. 
and issue a certificate of occupancy. 
</P>
<P>
Yaffee said the Pasadena Community Development Commission abused its discretion 
by refusing to consider deteriorated conditions at the shopping center when it 
and, later, the Board of Directors vetoed Cho's proposal for the Fair Oaks 
Department Store. 
</P>
<P>
The city said Cho's store would detract from redevelopment goals for the area 
and would increase traffic. But Yaffee said that conditions at the shopping 
center have already deteriorated to such an extent that major stores are 
reluctant to locate there. 
</P>
</TEXT>
