4 HOMELESS SUE N.Y. FOR TOILETS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Four homeless people have filed a class-action suit against the city seeking 
clean and safe public toilets. 
</P>
<P>
The suit filed Wednesday against the city and two transit agencies contends 
that the failure to provide toilets constitutes a public nuisance. 
</P>
<P>
It says the plaintiffs, three men and a woman, are "forced to endure continual 
embarrassment, humiliation, physical injury and hazardous conditions." 
</P>
<P>
The Legal Action Center for the Homeless, which represents the plaintiffs, said 
the lack of public toilets in the city is a hardship not only for the homeless 
but also for pregnant women, the elderly, tourists and outdoor workers. 
</P>
<P>
A report by the center said that of 105 Transit Authority restrooms surveyed, 
fewer than one-third were open to the public, and half of those were in bad 
condition. 
</P>
