</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TORONTO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Victor Kiam, owner of Remington Products Inc., has been charged with misleading 
advertising. 
</P>
<P>
Also charged are Remington Products Canada of Mississauga, Ontario, and Grey 
Advertising of Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
The charges under Canada's Competition Act deal with commercials aired in 1987 
and 1988 for the Micro Screen Ultimate Electric Shaver. 
</P>
<P>
One charge alleges that the commercials make performance claims without 
adequate substantiation. The other charge is under a general provision that 
prohibits misleading advertising. 
</P>
<P>
For Kiam, conviction could mean five years in prison or a fine for which the 
act sets no maximum. 
</P>
<P>
The commercials in question claim that the Micro Screen Ultimate shaves as 
close as a blade and closer than any other electric shaver. 
</P>
