<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
AIRLINE RETIREMENT RULE UPHELD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. 7th Circuit Court of Appeals in Chicago has upheld a 30-year-old 
Federal Aviation Administration rule that forces commercial airline pilots to 
retire at age 60. 
</P>
<P>
The three-judge panel voted 2 to 1 Wednesday against a group of airline pilots 
who sought to have the rule overturned. 
</P>
<P>
But all three judges voiced reservations about the ruling. The senior judge, 
Hubert L. Will, wrote a strongly worded dissent. The FAA established the 
retirement rule in 1960 and has argued consistently that allowing pilots to fly 
beyond age 60 would be dangerous. 
</P>
<P>
Critics say pilots in their 60s have experience that benefits passengers, and 
cite the 1989 crash of a United Airlines jetliner in Sioux City, Iowa, to back 
their case. A 57-year-old pilot landed a jet, despite a crippled hydraulic 
system. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief; Wire 
</P>
</TYPE>
