<HEADLINE>
<P>
BREEDERS CROWN; 
</P>
<P>
SCENIC REGAL NOT GOING BACK FOR SECONDS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ED SCHUYLER, ASSOCIATED PRESS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
POMPANO BEACH, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Scenic Regal is a lady in waiting. 
</P>
<P>
Friday night, she will try to become a queen of the sport she has served so 
well when she attempts to win the Mare Trot, one of eight Breeders Crown 
harness races contested at Pompano Park. 
</P>
<P>
A victory would be the first for the 8-year-old mare after finishing second 
three consecutive times in the race. 
</P>
<P>
To accomplish that, she will have to beat eight rivals including the 4-year-old 
Peace Corps, who won the 2-year-old Filly Trot in 1988 and the 3-year-old Filly 
Trot last year. Only two horses have won three Breeders Crown races -- the mare 
Grades Singing and the horse Mack Lobell, both trotters. 
</P>
<P>
"This is just a perfect mare in all ways," said Harold Story, who drives Scenic 
Regal for owner Dr. Terrance McGee, a veterinarian from Marlboro, Mass. "She 
does absolutely nothing wrong, on the track or in the barn." 
</P>
<P>
Scenic Regal has made 122 starts and has scored 68 wins, 23 seconds and eight 
thirds, with earnings of $956,140. This year, she has eight wins, six seconds 
and one third in 17 races. 
</P>
<P>
Scenic Regal drew the No. 7 post. Peace Corps, who has raced this year in 
Scandinavia and Europe, drew the No. 4 post. 
</P>
<P>
While Peace Corps will try to do what only two others have done, Beach Towel 
will try to make history in the 3-year-old Pace. 
</P>
<P>
A victory or a second-place finish in the $366,933 race would make Beach Towel, 
who has 17 wins and four seconds in 22 starts this year, the first harness 
racehorse to win $2 million in one year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Wire 
</P>
